      <text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>Obtain an estimate of the point of intersection of the curves \(y = {@f1@}\) and \(y = {@f2@}\).</p>
<figure class="HELM_figure">
    [[jsxgraph]]
    const brd = JXG.JSXGraph.initBoard(divid, {boundingbox: [-1, 3, 5, -3], axis: true, showCopyright: false});
    const f1 = brd.jc.snippet('{#f1#}', true, 'x', true);
    brd.create('functiongraph', [f1]);
    const f2 = brd.jc.snippet('{#f2#}', true, 'x', true);
    brd.create('functiongraph', [f2], {strokeColor: 'red'});
    [[/jsxgraph]]
</figure>
<p>Use one iteration of the Newtonâ€“Raphson method with \(x_0 = {@x0@}\) to find your estimate.</p>
<p>Give it here to \(2\) d.p.</p>
<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>In order to find the point of intersection of the curves \(y = {@f1@}\) and \(y = {@f2@}\), we must find a root of the function \(f(x) = {@f1@} - {@f2@}\).</p>
<p>First we find the derivative of \(f\), which is given by</p>
\[f'(x) = {@df@}.\]
<p>Next, we apply the formula:</p>
\[x_{1} = x_0 - \frac{f(x_0)}{f'(x_0)}\]
<p>With \(x_0 = {@x0@}\), we get</p>
\[x_1 = {@x0@} - \frac{{@decimalplaces(subst(x0, x, f), 4)@}}{{@decimalplaces(subst(x0, x, df), 4)@}} = {@ta1@}, \quad \text{to 2 d.p.}\]
<p>We can visualise the process in the following graph.</p>
[[jsxgraph]]
const brd = JXG.JSXGraph.initBoard(divid, {boundingbox: [0.5, 2, 3, -2], axis: true, showCopyright: false});
const f = brd.jc.snippet('{#f#}', true, 'x', true);
const plot = brd.create('functiongraph', [f]);
const x0 = brd.create('point', [{#x0#}, 0], {name: 'x_0', fixed: true});
const y0 = brd.create('point', [function() {return x0.X();}, function() {return f(x0.X());}],
    {withLabel: false, size: 2, strokeColor: 'none'});
const auxl0 = brd.create('line', [x0, y0], {dash: 2, strokeColor: 'red', straightFirst: false, straightLast: false});
const x1 = brd.create('point', [{#float(x1)#}, 0], {name: 'x_1', fixed: true, strokeColor: 'green', fillColor: 'green'});
const l1 = brd.create('line', [y0, x1], {strokeColor: 'green'});
[[/jsxgraph]]]]></text>
